{"id":"1608.01091","submitter":"Yichen Huang","authors":"Yichen Huang and Yong-Liang Zhang and Xie Chen","title":"Out-of-time-ordered correlators in many-body localized systems","comments":"published version with updated references","journal-ref":"Annalen der Physik 529 (7), 1600318 (Rapid Research Letter), 2017","doi":"10.1002/andp.201600318","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.dis-nn","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In many-body localized systems, propagation of information forms a light cone\nthat grows logarithmically with time. However, local changes in energy or other\nconserved quantities typically spread only within a finite distance. Is it\npossible to detect the logarithmic light cone generated by a local perturbation\nfrom the response of a local operator at a later time? We numerically calculate\nvarious correlators in the random-field Heisenberg chain. While the equilibrium\nretarded correlator $A(t=0)B(t>0)$ is not sensitive to the unbounded\ninformation propagation, the out-of-time-ordered correlator\n$A(t=0)B(t>0)A(t=0)B(t>0)$ can detect the logarithmic light cone. We relate\nout-of-time-ordered correlators to the Lieb-Robinson bound in many-body\nlocalized systems, and show how to detect the logarithmic light cone with\nretarded correlators in specially designed states. Furthermore, we study the\ntemperature dependence of the logarithmic light cone using out-of-time-ordered\ncorrelators.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 3 Aug 2016 07:02:15 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 8 Aug 2016 23:59:25 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Sat, 10 Dec 2016 12:12:21 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-08-07"}
